    ("Representative Concentration Pathways (RCPs) and SSPs represent:", ["measured current atmospheric conditions at monitoring stations", "different scenarios of future greenhouse gas emissions and development", "only the most likely single future climate trajectory ahead", "historical climate data from the past 100 years exactly"], 1, "Scenarios explore a range of possible emission futures."),
    ("Parameterization in climate models refers to:", ["setting all parameters to exactly zero for simplicity", "representing sub-grid-scale processes with simplified approximations", "ignoring all processes smaller than the grid resolution", "measuring every molecule in the atmosphere individually"], 1, "Clouds, turbulence, and other small-scale processes are parameterized."),
    ("Climate sensitivity refers to the temperature change from:", ["doubling the amount of solar energy received by Earth", "doubling atmospheric CO₂ concentration from pre-industrial levels", "reducing all greenhouse gases to zero immediately today", "moving Earth's orbit to twice its current distance from Sun"], 1, "Estimated at ~2.5-4°C for a doubling of CO₂."),
    ("Ensemble runs in climate modeling involve:", ["running one model once and trusting that single result", "running multiple simulations with varied initial conditions or model physics", "using only one emission scenario for all future projections", "discarding all results that show any significant warming"], 1, "Ensembles reveal the range of possible outcomes."),
    ("Ocean components in climate models are important because oceans:", ["have no effect on atmospheric climate or weather patterns", "store vast amounts of heat and CO₂, moderating climate change", "only affect coastal areas and not the global climate", "respond instantly to atmospheric changes with no lag"], 1, "Ocean thermal inertia and carbon uptake are critical climate factors."),
    ("Downscaling climate projections provides:", ["less useful information than global model output alone", "regional detail by applying global projections to local scales", "only decorative maps with no scientific applications", "global averages that are more useful than regional data"], 1, "Regional impacts require downscaled information for planning."),
    ("Model intercomparison projects (like CMIP) help by:", ["ensuring all models produce identical results always", "comparing multiple models to identify robust findings and sources of uncertainty", "replacing all models with a single agreed-upon model", "only creating competition between modeling groups for funding"], 1, "Multi-model agreement increases confidence in projections."),
    ("Aerosol representation in climate models is challenging because:", ["aerosols have no effect on climate at all in any way", "aerosol composition, distribution, and cloud interactions are complex and uncertain", "all aerosols behave identically regardless of composition", "aerosols only exist in laboratory settings currently"], 1, "Aerosol-cloud interactions are a major source of model uncertainty."),
    ("Tipping points in climate models represent:", ["normal gradual changes that are easily reversible later", "thresholds beyond which abrupt, potentially irreversible changes occur", "only theoretical concepts with no real-world significance", "temperature levels where all warming stops naturally"], 1, "Ice sheet collapse or forest dieback could trigger abrupt shifts."),
    ("Cumulative emissions determine:", ["only daily weather patterns in specific locations today", "the total amount of warming, regardless of when emissions occurred", "nothing about future climate conditions on any timescale", "only local air quality and not global temperature change"], 1, "The carbon budget concept links total CO₂ to temperature targets."),
    ("Climate model output should be interpreted as:", ["exact predictions of specific future weather days and events", "projections of climate statistics (averages, extremes) under given scenarios", "completely unreliable guesses with no scientific foundation", "only relevant to scientists and not to policy decisions"], 1, "Models provide probability ranges, not precise predictions."),
    ("Coupling atmosphere, ocean, ice, and land in models is important because:", ["each component operates independently without interactions", "feedbacks between components strongly influence the overall climate response", "only the atmosphere matters for understanding climate change", "coupling makes models simpler and faster to compute"], 1, "Earth is a coupled system; model components must interact."),
    ("Bias correction adjusts model output to:", ["make all models agree perfectly with each other always", "reduce systematic differences between model simulations and observations", "ignore all observed data in favor of model predictions", "increase uncertainty in the model projection results"], 1, "Statistical methods align model output with observed climate."),
    ("Earth system models (ESMs) extend climate models by including:", ["only physical processes and excluding all chemistry entirely", "biogeochemical cycles (carbon, nitrogen) and dynamic vegetation", "only atmospheric processes without ocean or land components", "only past climate conditions without any future projections"], 1, "ESMs capture feedbacks between climate and biogeochemistry."),
